se}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57806","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57806"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 57-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-hour history of severe central chest pain radiating to her left arm. She feels nauseated and appears diaphoretic. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 95/min, blood pressure 145/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Her ECG is shown here (\u003Ca href=\u0022https://emedici.com/storage/media/e015e9ff-debc-4624-80b7-4485863c6f14.jpg\u0022\u003Eimage\u003C/a\u003E).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following areas of the heart is undergoing acute myocardial injury?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anterolateral wall","Inferior wall","Lateral wall","Posterior wall","Anterior wall"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ECG shows ST-segment elevation in leads V2-V4 (anterior wall), as well as leads I, aVL and V5-V6 (lateral wall), which is indicative of an acute \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterolateral wall\u003C/strong\u003E myocardial infarction. ST elevation in the precordial leads along with the high lateral leads (I and aVL) strongly suggests an acute occlusion of the proximal left anterior descending (LAD) artery, with involvement of diagonal branches or the left circumflex artery. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Einferior wall\u003C/strong\u003E infarction would show ST-segment elevation in leads II, III, and aVF, which is not seen here. The inferior wall is usually supplied by the right coronary artery or left circumflex artery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIsolated \u003Cstrong\u003Elateral wall\u003C/strong\u003E infarction would show ST-segment elevation predominantly in leads I, aVL, V5, and V6, without the changes in V1-V4 seen here. The lateral wall is typically supplied by branches of the left circumflex artery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eposterior wall\u003C/strong\u003E infarction typically presents with ST-segment depression and tall R waves in leads V1-V3, often accompanied by inferior or lateral changes. These features are not present in this ECG.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn isolated \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterior wall\u003C/strong\u003E infarction would show ST-segment elevation primarily in leads V1-V4, without the lateral wall involvement (V5-V6, I, aVL) seen in this ECG.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of ST-segment elevation in both the anterior (V1-V4) and lateral (V5-V6, I, aVL) leads indicates that this is an anterolateral infarction, likely due to occlusion of the left anterior descending artery with involvement of its diagonal branches or the left circumflex artery. This pattern of infarction typically involves a larger area of myocardium and may be associated with a worse prognosis, emphasising the importance of prompt recognition and management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["ST-segment elevation in specific ECG leads can localise the area of myocardial injury.","Anterolateral myocardial infarction is indicated by ST-segment elevation in leads V1-V6.","Correct interpretation of ECG changes is crucial for appropriate management of myocardial infarction."],"references":["Ahmad M, Mehta P, Reddivari AKR, et al. Percutaneous Coronary Intervention. [Updated 2021 Jan 16]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2021 Jan. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK556123/?report=classicSattar Y, Chhabra L. Electrocardiogram. [Updated 2023 Jun 5]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK549803/","Sawyer, D. B., \u0026 Vasan, R. S. (2017). Encyclopedia of cardiovascular research and medicine. Elsevier.","Burns, E, Butter, R. Anterior Myocardial Infarction. Life in the Fast Lane. 2024. Available from: https://litfl.com/anterior-myocardial-infarction-ecg-library/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43265"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14599"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19305"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19305","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19305"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e015e9ff-debc-4624-80b7-4485863c6f14.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e015e9ff-debc-4624-80b7-4485863c6f14.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":420,"height":275}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43265","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43265"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-27T17:35:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-27T17:36:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7292"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57806"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"descript